245
00:33:03,211 --> 00:33:05,775
You filled his head with your fairy tales.

246
00:33:05,775 --> 00:33:07,363
Pari: I only wanted what was best for him.

247
00:33:07,363 --> 00:33:08,159
Farrokh: Well, there you go!

248
00:33:09,189 --> 00:33:11,651
This is your idea of what’s best for him.

249
00:33:12,414 --> 00:33:13,177
Are you happy now?

250
00:33:13,177 --> 00:33:14,565
Pari: We still don’t know what happened!

251
00:33:14,565 --> 00:33:17,518
Farrokh: What more do you need to happen? He’s left us in this strange city.

252
00:33:17,518 --> 00:33:20,784
Pari: Farrokh, I know Babak. He wouldn’t do this without a reason.

253
00:33:20,784 --> 00:33:23,680
Farrokh: Oh, I know how well you know him.

254
00:33:37,340 --> 00:33:42,159
He brought us here to show us all this mess.

255
00:33:42,880 --> 00:33:45,178
Farrokh: He’s destroyed our honor.

256
00:33:45,810 --> 00:33:48,499
I’ve never been so ashamed in my life.

257
00:33:48,499 --> 00:33:50,499
Pari: Enough with your honor and pride!

258
00:33:51,083 --> 00:33:52,903
Farrokh: Now you’re mocking my honor?

259
00:33:53,176 --> 00:33:56,242
Pari: To hell with your honor! My son is missing!

260
00:33:56,360 --> 00:33:58,744
Farrokh: Last time you talked like this, you ended up in the streets

261
00:33:58,127 --> 00:34:00,327
with a baby in your arms.

262
00:34:04,656 --> 00:34:06,877
Astaghfirullah (seeking "forgiveness")

263
00:34:21,720 --> 00:34:24,480
Pari: What do you want from me?

264
00:34:25,280 --> 00:34:29,252
Farrokh: What do you want from me?

265
00:34:29,517 --> 00:34:32,489
If honor doesn’t matter to you, why did you stay with me?

266
00:34:32,879 --> 00:34:36,496
I didn’t force you!

267
00:35:07,770 --> 00:35:10,737
Farrokh: Let’s go. We need to find a place to stay.

268
00:35:35,664 --> 00:35:39,060
Bagheri: Unfortunately, the police have no trace of him.

269
00:35:39,060 --> 00:35:41,060
Farrokh: How is that even possible?

270
00:35:41,060 --> 00:35:44,915
Bagheri: His student visa expired a year ago. He’s been here illegally. (serious)

271
00:35:44,915 --> 00:35:48,674
Farrokh: He’s been here for years. Can’t they do anything else?

272
00:35:49,292 --> 00:35:53,529
Bagheri: Hajj Agha, it’s not that simple. He needs to be officially recognized as missing.

273
00:35:53,529 --> 00:35:56,007
Farrokh: Please, see what you can do.

274
00:35:56,007 --> 00:35:58,068
Bagheri: We’ll figure something out.

275
00:35:58,274 --> 00:36:00,154
Farrokh: I didn’t force you!

276
00:36:00,154 --> 00:36:03,450
You’ve been with me all these years, but you’ve always dreamed of a different life.

277
00:36:03,450 --> 00:36:04,775
I didn’t force you! (dreamy)

278
00:36:06,777 --> 00:36:09,301
Farrokh: What are you doing?

279
00:36:10,714 --> 00:36:11,636
Are you okay, Pari?

280
00:36:11,636 --> 00:36:13,166
Let’s go outside and get some air.

281
00:36:20,039 --> 00:36:26,202
Bagheri: As soon as there’s any news, they’ll inform us. I emphasized that this matter is important to the embassy.

282
00:36:26,202 --> 00:36:29,831
Farrokh: Thank you, sir. What else can we do?

283
00:36:29,831 --> 00:36:33,295
Bagheri: Honestly, there’s nothing more we can do. We just have to wait.

284
00:36:33,295 --> 00:36:36,795
Pari: No, sir. We can’t just wait.

285
00:36:37,472 --> 00:36:43,280
Farrokh: Tell me, where do Iranians usually go here? What do they do? Is there a center? A mosque?

286
00:36:43,280 --> 00:36:47,359
Official: There’s the cultural center at the embassy, but your son had no connection with us.

287
00:36:47,359 --> 00:36:51,151
As for the mosque, you might want to check out the church instead.

288
00:36:51,151 --> 00:36:52,857
Farrokh: Why a church?

289
00:36:52,857 --> 00:36:54,857
Official: Hajj Agha, things are really bad here.

290
00:36:55,301 --> 00:36:56,642
Farrokh: Speak freely.

291
00:36:57,319 --> 00:37:02,188
Official: Iranians here are in a terrible state. Many convert to Christianity to seek asylum.

292
00:37:02,188 --> 00:37:04,600
Everywhere you go, you see addicted migrants.

293
00:37:04,600 --> 00:37:08,425
Even our women and young men sell themselves for a bit of money

294
00:37:08,425 --> 00:37:10,044
Farrokh: I understand perfectly.

295
00:37:10,044 --> 00:37:14,589
Official: Now, your son may not be caught up in all this, but I had to tell you.

296
00:37:15,796 --> 00:37:17,310
Farrokh: So where do we even start?

297
00:37:18,680 --> 00:37:22,735
Bagheri: Start with this area. It’s where most of the migrants are.

298
00:37:22,735 --> 00:37:27,028
The Iranian shops here have the Zoroastrian symbol.

299
00:37:27,028 --> 00:37:30,785
Many of them are involved in human smuggling.

300
00:37:30,785 --> 00:37:34,599
If you see them, ask around, maybe someone knows your son.

301
00:37:46,529 --> 00:37:49,529
Farrokh: ...Pari, don’t stand by the window... Pari, move away...

302
00:43:05,199 --> 00:43:08,479
Preacher: The story is just beginning.

303
00:43:15,745 --> 00:43:19,199
[Clapping]
God knows you’re not perfect.

304
00:43:20,598 --> 00:43:25,400
But you’re the ones who started this journey.

305
00:43:27,820 --> 00:43:31,589
[ Music]
No, unfortunately, I don’t know him.

306
00:43:31,589 --> 00:43:33,589
Farrokh: Sorry for bothering you.

307
00:43:33,914 --> 00:43:39,928
Woman: You’re not a bother. This is the house of God, and we are all His children.

308
00:43:40,399 --> 00:43:46,159
[Worshiping]

309
00:43:47,120 --> 00:43:51,859
Woman: If there’s anything we can do to help, we’d be happy to.

310
00:43:58,440 --> 00:44:01,600
Farrokh: Nobody knows him.

311
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:08,634
Pari: Do you remember? He loved the sea.

312
00:44:08,634 --> 00:44:11,577
When he was little, he used to say, “I want to be a pirate!”

313
00:44:11,577 --> 00:44:18,289
Farrokh: It’s winter now. We won’t find him at sea.

314
00:44:18,289 --> 00:44:22,940
You’re not eating, not sleeping well, and you’ve even stopped praying.

315
00:44:22,940 --> 00:44:26,100
I’m more worried about you now.

316
00:44:41,160 --> 00:44:45,760
We’ve been here a month already. We’re both on edge, and our money’s running out.

317
00:44:45,760 --> 00:44:49,057
Wandering around like this is pointless.

318
00:44:49,557 --> 00:44:51,882
Pari: But we’re not looking in the right places.

319
00:44:53,148 --> 00:44:55,161
Farrokh: So where should we be looking?

320
00:44:57,015 --> 00:45:02,213
Pari: I feel like Babak was running away from anything that reminded him of Iran.

321
00:45:02,213 --> 00:45:03,802
He didn’t come back to Iran,

322
00:45:03,802 --> 00:45:06,863
and he had no connection with the Iranians here either.

323
00:45:07,128 --> 00:45:09,759
He didn’t even write in Persian anymore.

324
00:45:09,992 --> 00:45:13,592
Farrokh: Then where do we search now?

325
00:45:15,594 --> 00:45:17,594
What do you think?

326
00:45:28,590 --> 00:45:31,526
Pari: I don’t know.

327
00:45:31,703 --> 00:45:34,852
Farrokh: I love Babak like my own son.

328
00:45:35,117 --> 00:45:37,177
He carries my name.

329
00:45:38,303 --> 00:45:40,357
I’ll never abandon him.

330
00:45:41,652 --> 00:45:44,125
I’ve asked Bagheri to prepare a request for Interpol.

331
00:45:44,360 --> 00:45:47,640
If they find him anywhere in Europe or the U.S., we’ll be informed.

332
00:45:47,640 --> 00:45:50,436
We’ll wait in Iran, and if they get any news, we’ll come back.

333
00:45:51,702 --> 00:45:54,665
Even if there’s a 1% chance he’s still here,

334
00:45:54,665 --> 00:45:56,329
we can hire a good private investigator.

335
00:45:56,329 --> 00:46:02,529
Pari: Farrokh, I can’t leave here without Babak.

336
00:46:08,199 --> 00:46:11,199
‏ah

337
00:46:24,742 --> 00:46:29,622
No more wine for me.

338
00:46:32,240 --> 00:46:36,120
Neither the murky red.

339
00:46:36,503 --> 00:46:38,503
Nor the bright one.

340
00:46:42,560 --> 00:46:44,515
I’m thirsty.

341
00:46:44,515 --> 00:46:47,517
Thirsty for my own blood,

342
00:46:47,517 --> 00:46:49,517
spilled in the square.

343
00:49:42,303 --> 00:49:44,332
[Whispering]

344
00:49:44,509 --> 00:49:46,509
No more wine...

345
00:49:47,451 --> 00:49:49,451
I’m so thirsty

346
00:49:51,734 --> 00:49:52,957
Pari...

347
00:49:53,657 --> 00:49:54,357
Pari...

348
00:50:03,419 --> 00:50:05,653
I was worried sick... where were you?

349
00:50:21,518 --> 00:50:23,284
Pari: I thought it was Babak

350
00:50:23,843 --> 00:50:24,547
... Farrokh?

351
00:50:25,626 --> 00:50:26,705
What’s wrong? Are you okay?

352
00:50:28,824 --> 00:50:31,093
Farrokh: I feel a little dizzy...

353
00:50:35,584 --> 00:50:38,544
Pari: I couldn’t stop myself, I thought it was him.

354
00:50:40,281 --> 00:50:41,104
I’m sorry.

355
00:50:41,764 --> 00:50:42,424
Farrokh: No...

356
00:50:43,278 --> 00:50:44,333
you should forgive me...

357
00:50:46,217 --> 00:50:48,142
I wasn’t the father I should have been.

358
00:50:48,142 --> 00:50:50,173
Pari: No, Farrokh, you didn’t fail.

359
00:50:50,700 --> 00:50:52,669
Farrokh: I was just doing my duty.

360
00:50:53,924 --> 00:50:55,179
That’s...

361
00:50:55,179 --> 00:50:57,179
not enough to be a father.

362
00:51:01,830 --> 00:51:03,858
I knew there was a danger

363
00:51:06,800 --> 00:51:09,961
, but I still let him come here.

364
00:51:13,258 --> 00:51:15,337
I wanted to be with you.

365
00:51:18,457 --> 00:51:20,944
I wanted you to be mine.

366
00:51:24,062 --> 00:51:25,944
Pari: I am your wife.

367
00:51:27,875 --> 00:51:29,011
Farrokh: My wife?

368
00:51:32,205 --> 00:51:33,604
You’re like them.

369
00:51:35,841 --> 00:51:38,276
There’s something inside you.

370
00:51:40,762 --> 00:51:43,248
I’ve seen it with my own eyes

371
00:51:43,748 --> 00:51:46,397
, it’s torn so many lives apart.

372
00:51:49,967 --> 00:51:53,537
So many good people lost...

373
00:51:55,068 --> 00:51:57,609
I tried to protect you.

374
00:52:00,170 --> 00:52:02,419
But now... the choice is yours.

375
00:52:03,714 --> 00:52:06,073
Pari: Why are you talking like this, Farrokh?

376
00:52:06,820 --> 00:52:08,944
You’re scaring me.

377
00:52:10,640 --> 00:52:12,336
Farrokh: I don’t know.

378
00:52:17,556 --> 00:52:19,479
My mind’s all over the place.

379
00:52:25,013 --> 00:52:26,489
Come on, let’s go.

380
00:52:28,225 --> 00:52:30,225
Tomorrow is another day.

381
00:53:09,224 --> 00:53:11,852
Farrokh: Pari, make me some tea with candy.

382
00:53:12,029 --> 00:53:13,147
Pari: Did you take your pill?

383
00:53:15,359 --> 00:53:17,012
Farrokh: Yeah, but my stomach’s a bit upset.

384
00:53:55,724 --> 00:53:56,705
Pari: Farrokh?

385
00:54:00,472 --> 00:54:02,472
Farrokh? get up, it’s ready...

386
00:54:02,443 --> 00:54:03,276
Farrokh?

387
00:54:05,689 --> 00:54:06,646
Farrokh?

388
00:54:09,236 --> 00:54:10,266
Farrokh?

389
00:54:14,799 --> 00:54:15,505
Farrokh?

390
00:54:16,417 --> 00:54:18,005
Farrokh?

391
00:54:19,122 --> 00:54:20,239
Help!

392
00:54:44,078 --> 00:54:46,190
Farrokh? Can you hear me?

393
00:54:48,549 --> 00:54:50,731
Hold on, Farrokh!

394
01:00:30,944 --> 01:00:33,283
[Whispering]

395
01:00:33,283 --> 01:00:35,283
No more wine for me—

396
01:00:36,175 --> 01:00:38,119
Neither the murky red,

397
01:00:38,175 --> 01:00:40,301
Nor the crystal-clear white.

398
01:00:41,012 --> 01:00:43,242
I thirst for my own blood,

399
01:00:43,242 --> 01:00:46,946
Spilled on the battlefield.

400
01:00:52,827 --> 01:00:55,802
Strike with your sword,

401
01:00:56,819 --> 01:00:58,819
Your sharp blade!

402
01:00:59,086 --> 01:01:00,486
Strike!

403
01:01:01,235 --> 01:01:06,384
Strike, until the head spins away from the body.

404
01:01:07,884 --> 01:01:10,029
Build a mountain from these fallen heads,

405
01:01:12,269 --> 01:01:13,775
Tear me apart!

406
01:01:19,719 --> 01:01:21,971
Do not silence me!

407
01:01:24,325 --> 01:01:26,325
Do not heed my words!

408
01:01:27,034 --> 01:01:29,908
I must walk into the flames!

409
01:01:30,940 --> 01:01:32,820
The fire, my child,

410
01:01:34,718 --> 01:01:36,759
Yet I must burn,

411
01:01:38,634 --> 01:01:40,747
So that I may become the fire.

412
01:45:04,716 --> 01:45:07,830
Strike now, O bringer of chaos,

413
01:45:10,188 --> 01:45:13,840
Break that jug upon the stone,

414
01:45:20,162 --> 01:45:23,931
So I no longer draw from the flowing stream,

415
01:45:25,164 --> 01:45:28,164
Nor dip my hands in its waters.

416
01:45:30,565 --> 01:45:33,308
I will forsake the cup-bearer's task,

417
01:45:37,166 --> 01:45:40,349
And let myself drown in the ocean.

418
01:28:41,026 --> 01:28:45,208
I wanted him to live a way that I couldn't do myself.

419
01:28:46,201 --> 01:28:47,194
I ...

420
01:28:47,954 --> 01:28:50,772
never found the courage myself.

421
01:28:51,365 --> 01:28:54,404
I always thought they wouldn’t allow it.

422
01:28:54,669 --> 01:28:57,350
But the truth is, I didn’t dare to.
